<div class="page-card" id="document-page">
    <h1 id="title">HexyComb Documentation</h1>

    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>HexyComb is a simple two player strategy game built using Unity WebGL, React, Express, MongoDB, and WebSockets.</p>

    <h2>Questions</h2>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What is the intended purpose of your application?</h4>
        <p>I have been working on HexyComb for a whole semester now, and I wanted to make it accessible across the web. HexyComb itself is a fun game to play, but this webpage serves not only as a place where new players can explore the game of Hive, but also play against other random players or even send invites to play with their friends. It also comes with an interesting side effect of being able to store games as a list of moves, which over time, can be used to train AI on which move is the best.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What work has been completed for this milestone?</h4>
        <p>The foundation for many of the endpoints, a basic style that applies to all handlebars, React is integrated into the /play endpoint and is bundled with Webpack</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What work is left and how do you plan to complete it?</h4>
        <p>With only about a week left in the semester, it's difficult for me to choose which features I want to implement. Since I have the endpoints for premium and an update player count, I will likely start with those two features. Learning from Project 1, and, considering how much I've struggled already, I'll be keeping my scope short.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>How are you using React?</h4>
        <p>Since most of my time was spent learning about Unity Brotli and .br files, I did not spend much time creating components. Instead I setup React for the future, ensuring that I can render things like instructions or player/profile statuses.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What data are you storing in your MongoDB?</h4>
        <p>I store data related to user accounts, such as usernames, passwords, premium status and session data, but I also store match invites, though it has no effect yet. As mentioned before, I plan on storing games as lists of moves, but I am also looking into player statistics or perhaps a ranking system.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>What is your profit model?</h4>
        <p>My original plan for the profit model was to have it so that the expansion pieces, like the ladybug, pillbug and mosquito would be added. However due to limited time, I may just have it so that premium members can use Online services while regular users can only play locally. However, I am also considering having it so that premium players can view their past games.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>Do you have a plan for going above and beyond? If so, what is it?</h4>
        <p>The fact that this UnityWebGL build can run on the web, let alone the fact that this game was created from scratch over the course of the semester seems to me like above and beyond. However, there are many other features that I wish to include to go even further above and beyond. In all honesty, I'd prefer to have a cool application I can talk about in job interviews as opposed to some letters on a piece of paper.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question">
        <h4>If you borrowed code or code fragments, where did you get them from?</h4>
        <p>I spent a considerably long time, slogging through roadblocks just to get the game playable on the web. Though I didn't copy from the <a href="https://react-unity-webgl.dev/docs/miscellaneous-instructions/compressed-builds-and-server-configuration">React Unity WebGL documentation</a> directly, I did the equivalent of tracing a picture, going back and forth constantly between documentation to get my build working. I also searched extensively across the web for information about .br files. Thankfully, I came across a pleasing <a href="https://miltoncandelero.github.io/unity-webgl-compression">webpage</a> that made it easier to understand.</p>
    </div>
    
    <h2>Available Endpoints</h2>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /login</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresSecure, requiresLogout</p>
        <p>Renders the login page.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>POST /login</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresSecure, requiresLogout</p>
        <p>Attempts to authenticate a user and create a session.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /signup</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresSecure, requiresLogout</p>
        <p>Renders the signup page.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>POST /signup</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresSecure, requiresLogout</p>
        <p>Creates a new user account.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /logout</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresSecure, requiresLogin</p>
        <p>Logs the user out and destroys their session.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>POST /premium/toggle</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresLogin</p>
        <p>Toggles the user's premium status (profit model).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>POST /invite/create</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresLogin</p>
        <p>Creates a new invite‑based match.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /invite/:gameId</h3>
        <p><strong>Middleware:</strong> requiresLogin</p>
        <p>Retrieves an invite match by ID.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /playerCount</h3>
        <p>No middleware.</p>
        <p>Returns the number of connected WebSocket players. Will be used to display number of Online players.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /play</h3>
        <p>No middleware.</p>
        <p>Serves the Unity WebGL + React game client.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="endpoint">
        <h3>GET /documentation</h3>
        <p>No middleware.</p>
        <p>Renders this documentation page.</p>
    </div>

</div>
